      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Refactor HTTP egress around external proxy enforcement",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nThis PR removes OpenClaw's old broad in-process SSRF guard architecture and replaces it with a smaller, centralized HTTP egress model.\n\nThe new architecture is:\n\n- `proxy.enabled=true` plus an operator-managed external proxy is the high-assurance SSRF and egress-control boundary.\n- OpenClaw no longer maintains the old `fetchWithSsrFGuard` / DNS pinning / per-call SSRF policy matrix.\n- Stock direct mode still keeps a narrow safety guard for OpenClaw-owned fetches of arbitrary untrusted URLs.\n- App-owned outbound HTTP mechanics now go through a canonical egress helper instead of scattered fetch loops.\n\n## What Changed\n\n- Added centralized HTTP egress runtime in `src/infra/net/egress-fetch.ts`.\n- Migrated app-owned HTTP fetch paths for web fetch, media/input URL fetches, link understanding, citation redirects, marketplace archive downloads, skill install downloads, MCP HTTP, provider transport fetches, and related provider/plugin runtime fetches.\n- Removed `src/infra/net/fetch-guard.ts` and the old `fetchWithSsrFGuard` API.\n- Removed `openclaw/plugin-sdk/ssrf-runtime` from the public SDK surface as a breaking SDK change.\n- Removed old internal SSRF config/API knobs rather than preserving compatibility shims.\n- Replaced the old raw-channel-fetch check with `scripts/check-runtime-http-egress-boundary.mjs`, which blocks raw app-owned runtime fetches and retired SSRF guard vocabulary.\n- Updated doctor migrations and docs to point users toward `proxy.enabled` plus external proxy policy for high-assurance egress control.\n\n## Direct Mode Behavior\n\nWhen `proxy.enabled=false`, OpenClaw's canonical untrusted URL helper rejects local/private/internal destinations by default for OpenClaw-owned arbitrary URL fetches, including:\n\n- localhost and loopback\n- link-local targets\n- RFC1918 private networks\n- known metadata hosts\n- DNS results resolving to blocked ranges\n- redirect targets resolving to blocked ranges\n\nThis is intentionally a narrow stock safety guard, not a full SSRF defense.\n\n## Proxy Mode Behavior\n\nWhen `proxy.enabled=true`, OpenClaw routes app-owned HTTP egress through the configured external proxy and does not try to duplicate the proxy's comprehensive destination policy in application code.\n\nOperator-configured endpoints, fixed provider/vendor endpoints, and transport-owned fetch behavior are treated separately from arbitrary untrusted web URLs.\n\n## Breaking Changes\n\n- `openclaw/plugin-sdk/ssrf-runtime` is removed.\n- `fetchWithSsrFGuard`, `GUARDED_FETCH_MODE`, and related public SSRF-runtime exports are removed.\n- Old per-call SSRF policy/config knobs are retired.\n- Plugins should use ordinary `fetch` or the generic fetch runtime mechanics where appropriate, and rely on `proxy.enabled` plus external proxy policy for high-assurance egress enforcement.\n\n## Out Of Scope\n\nThis PR does not claim full SSRF coverage for:\n\n- Browser/CDP\n- subprocesses\n- sandbox executors\n- Docker/SSH boundaries\n- MCP stdio children\n- native addons\n- non-Node transport libraries\n\nThose remain separate defense-in-depth follow-ups.\n\n## Verification\n\nFocused local/Testbox/AWS proof was run on SHA `86fc2bb37342fbe65c0a9be21b21352902fc26d9`.\n\n- Focused unit and boundary tests for the egress helper, migrated fetch paths, plugin SDK contract, doctor migrations, and raw-fetch boundary checks.\n- `node scripts/check-runtime-http-egress-boundary.mjs`\n- `git diff --check`\n\n### Package Smoke\n\n- Provider/id: `blacksmith-testbox`, `tbx_01ktnh39xjqvzaqyvnk4tek7bf`\n- Actions run: `27188175859`\n- Verified the packaged SDK/public export surface after the removal.\n- Confirmed `openclaw/plugin-sdk/ssrf-runtime` is no longer exported.\n- Confirmed retired SSRF-specific fetch-runtime exports are absent from the package surface.\n\n### External Proxy E2E\n\n- Provider/id: `blacksmith-testbox`, `tbx_01ktnh8w3mgdvg1rgvd8z4tmr8`\n- Actions run: `27188302520`\n- Ran the external proxy E2E coverage for managed proxy routing.\n- Verified `proxy.enabled=true` routes runtime fetches through the configured external proxy.\n- Verified the proxy path still preserves expected fetch/redirect behavior for the covered helper scenarios.\n\n### AWS Product-Path Proof\n\n- Provider/id: `aws`, `cbx_5b6e8d6f5c94`\n- Ran live product-path proof against an AWS-hosted target/honeypot/proxy fixture.\n- Exercised OpenClaw product call paths rather than only helper-level calls, including:\n  - `web_fetch`\n  - link understanding\n  - citation redirect resolution\n  - remote media fetch\n  - input-file URL fetch\n  - marketplace archive download\n  - skill install download\n  - MCP HTTP same-origin fetch\n  - operator-configured endpoint fetch\n- Verified direct-mode untrusted URL paths block private/local/metadata-style targets before honeypot access.\n- Verified proxy-mode paths route through the proof proxy, with proxy allow/block decisions recorded.\n- Verified operator-configured endpoint behavior remains distinct from arbitrary untrusted URL behavior.\n- Verified the honeypot only saw the intentionally allowed operator-configured direct-mode case.\n\n### Targeted Marketplace Private-Redirect Proof\n\n- Provider/id: `aws`, `cbx_9bd99a3d87b9`\n- AWS runs: `run_b117a76160d3`, `run_714cc4109634`, `run_b47458f97c57`, `run_62972875e8be`, `run_636a90f349b7`, `run_0058dee2fdac`\n- Ran an additional live marketplace archive redirect proof because marketplace archive downloads only enter the archive download path when the initial source URL is archive-looking.\n- Used archive-looking marketplace source URLs:\n  - `/direct/archive-redirect-private.zip`\n  - `/proxy/archive-redirect-private.zip`\n- Verified both sources were classified as `zip` and entered `installPluginFromMarketplace` archive download behavior.\n- Direct mode:\n  - Public archive-looking fixture was contacted.\n  - Fixture redirected to an AWS private-IP honeypot URL.\n  - OpenClaw blocked the private redirect target with the direct-mode untrusted URL guard.\n  - Honeypot hits: 0.\n- Proxy mode:\n  - Request routed through the external proof proxy.\n  - Proxy logged allow for the public archive fixture.\n  - Proxy logged block for the private redirect target.\n  - Honeypot hits: 0.\n\n### Result\n\nAll planned proof rows passed for this refactor's stated scope.\n\nBrowser/CDP, subprocess, sandbox executor, Docker, SSH, MCP stdio, native addon, and non-Node transport boundaries were not in scope for this PR.\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\n\nBehavior addressed: OpenClaw-owned arbitrary URL fetch paths no longer depend on the old scattered `fetchWithSsrFGuard` architecture, while stock direct mode still blocks local/private/metadata-style targets for untrusted URL fetches.\n\nReal environment tested: Local focused tests, Blacksmith Testbox, and AWS Crabbox live network topology proof.\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch: Focused test lanes, runtime egress boundary check, package smoke, external proxy E2E, AWS product-path proof, and targeted marketplace archive redirect proof.\n\nEvidence after fix: Direct-mode untrusted URL fetches block private redirect targets before honeypot access; proxy-mode fetches route through the external proof proxy and are blocked by proxy policy before honeypot access.\n\nObserved result after fix: All planned proof rows passed for this refactor's stated scope.\n\nWhat was not tested: Browser/CDP, subprocess, sandbox executor, Docker, SSH, MCP stdio, native addon, and non-Node transport boundaries.\n",
